North Korea fires unidentified missile as Japan, US leaders meet Kanga Kong twitter TWEET More 
Seoul: North Korea test-fired an unidentified missile on Sunday from the country's north-west, South Korea's joint chiefs of staff said in a text message. 
The launch came from the same region where Kim Jong-un's regime fired a mid-range Musudan missile last October. Trump cheapens US-Mexico border wall Play Video North Korea close to test of ICBM North Korea close to test of ICBM

President Donald Trump was handed another legal defeat on Thursday when the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled to uphold a lower court's decision to block his controversial travel ban from seven Muslim-majority countries. More videos North Korea close to test of ICBM 
North Korean leader Kim Jong Un says that the isolated nuclear-capable country is close to test-launching an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM). 
South Korea's defence ministry said it couldn't confirm whether the projectile, which flew 500 kilometres over North Korea's eastern sea, was a long-range ballistic missile capable of reaching US territory that North Korea had threatened to test-launch in recent weeks. 
The launch comes as US President Donald Trump met with Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe in Florida. North Korea has launched a series of missiles and conducted three nuclear tests since Kim came to power about five years ago. SHARE
